text: hi everyone's red on my head you're the
internet's busiest music nerd and it's
time for a review of the new summer
walker album still over it this is the
newest full-length lp from singer and
songwriter summer walker the follow-up
to her breakout 2019 record over it one
of the biggest r b releases of that year
setting walker up to potentially become
one of the genre's biggest stars over
the next decade and still over it if you
couldn't tell from the title is sort of
like an attempt at repeating that
success with a fatter feature list track
list and a very similar attitude and
while there's no easy way to dive into
this stuff i feel like if you were to
listen to this album and simply leave
your engagement with summer walker there
you would only be getting part of the
story as walker's instagram antics and
all the speculation about her love life
her personal life has been cause for a
lot of headlines and tension which i
imagine has been really painful for her
to have these very intimate elements of
her life dissected so toxically over
social media but the whole purpose of
still over it seems to be to put out her
side of the story and also
turn lemons into lemonade i mean the
intro to the record features a message
from cardi b encouraging summer to do
exactly that but this record's not
simply born out of walker's personal
experiences it also very much feels like
a product of a post lemonade post
control world of course this record also
features scizza on the track no love and
also throws it back to the more sensual
vocal stylings that define the r b of
the 90s and early 2000s combine that
with the consistent themes of heartbreak
betrayal cheating sex and
walker learning to live for herself
you've got a pretty focused and cohesive
project and all these things
collectively make still over it in my
opinion a cut or two above over it but
in a way still over it still suffers
from some of the shortcomings of its
predecessor truth be told walker is not
the strongest vocalist out right now
there are pockets on this lp where
walker delivers some perfectly capable
and intimate vocal performances such as
the intro bitter but there are so many
other tracks on this lp where
the singing is so obviously touched up
when stuff like auto-tune does come into
play it seems less like an enhancement
and more like a crutch like with the
perfectly pitched harmonies on constant
[ __ ] or on x for a reason where it's
used on summer's voice to the point it
makes her singing come off stiff and
synthetic not to mention the
instrumental on this one sounds like a
ripoff of a ghost town dj's my boo so
sadly there's parts of this lp where
walker didn't really show out vocally in
the way that i hoped she would and there
are some other moments where the
songwriting leaves something to be
desired too after all there's 20 cuts on
this thing so every once in a while we
hit a flat chorus a half-baked song
structure or a song like circus that
meets a weirdly abrupt end the song
switch a person out the pacing on this
one is so tedious it's painful
occasionally the production can run a
little boring too i do appreciate the
consistently dark and smoky sound that
still over it tries to deliver from end
to end but sometimes this leads to beats
that come across a bit too barren like
the song reciprocate the rhythm on this
one is so skeletal and so basic it's
totally flavorless not to mention the
dodgy keys in the mix that are barely
there broken promises is a track where i
love what summer is singing about
dealing in rumors and trust issues but
musically this one just kind of goes
nowhere fast session 33 with its meager
guitar lines is another instance of a
song bringing more to a record
narratively than it does instrumentally
cause yeah while that guitar doesn't
really sound like much this song is
pretty essential to the track list in
that it shows summer reaching a breaking
point personally and emotionally she's
feeling abandoned and left out in the
cold and is essentially in a position
now where she has to accept the fate of
being this guy's fourth baby mama but
mind you that song is actually a
highlight on the record for me not only
does it have a great tune great
instrumental but it's one where
narratively summer finds the power to
move on coming out as empowered and
angry essentially listing out the
ridiculous behavior she dealt with in
the relationship all the [ __ ] it's a
seriously raw and relentless read that
goes from uh the dishonesty to the clout
chasing to a even some mommy issues
then we have the sierra outro on the
record which i think ends things off on
an even stronger note narratively
especially given the personal parallels
there to summer's story but sierra is
obviously like further down that road
and has shown in her own way that
there's like definitely light at the
other end of that tunnel which i hope is
the case for walker as well and when she
gets on the other side of that i hope
she uh
ends up kind of benefiting off of that
personally and and i hope that shows in
her music as well so look still over it
does have issues but i think summer
walker does make up for a lot of these
through her power to tell a story not
just on a single track but building all
of those into a larger narrative on the
album as a whole which is a difficult
task there's also something to be said
about her talent to channel her emotions
so intensely into a song the give no
[ __ ] energy for example on the song no
love is
absolutely liberating and probably a
couple of thousand babies have been uh
conceived to the song screw in in the
week or so that this album has been out
i think summer also proves herself on
this record to be great at curating a
series of beats and sounds that fit her
style really well like the silky dreamy
jazz notes all over the song and loyal
there's also the eerie insane who's
fantastic but very simple instrumental
features a sample from that legendary
cool and the gang song summer madness
closure is another track on the lp that
i think ends a little bit prematurely
but i do love the luscious beds of
strings laced into the beat on this one
then that right there is a flirty
summery banger with a neptune's
crossover on the beat also sounds like a
radio hit mid july and the early 2000s
so yeah there are some great highlights
in individual tracks on the lp and from
over it to here i think summer walker
has shown a lot of growth even if this
record isn't perfect feeling a strong
six to a light seven on this one tran
